<chapter xml:id="Sec-Ideals">
  <title>Ideals and Homomorphisms</title>
  <section xml:id="SubSec-Ideals-In-General">
    <title>Ideals in general</title>
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be commutative with identity and let
          <m>\set{I_{\alpha}}_{\alpha\in \Gamma}</m> be a family of ideals.
          Then <m>I = \bigcap\limits_{\alpha\in \Gamma} I_\alpha</m> is an ideal.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <proof>
      <p>
        It is clear that <m>0\in I</m>.
        Moreover, if <m>x,y\in I</m>,
        then <m>x,y\in I_\alpha</m> for all <m>\alpha</m>,
        so <m>x-y\in I_\alpha</m> and thus <m>x-y\in I</m>.
        Finally, if <m>x\in I</m> and <m>r\in R</m>,
        <m>rx\in I_\alpha</m> for all <m>\alpha</m>, and thus <m>rx\in I</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
      We can extend the notion of a principal ideal to ideals generated by any subset.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def_idealgeneration">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be a commutative ring with identity,
          and let <m>S\subseteq R</m> be a subset.
          Then
          <men xml:id="eq_idealgeneratedbyset">
            \langle S \rangle := \bigcap\limits_{\substack{J\supseteq S\\\text{ \(J\) is an ideal } } } J
          </men>
          is called the <term>ideal generated by <m>S</m></term>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
    	A consequence of <xref ref="def_idealgeneration" /> is the following theorem.
    </p>
	<theorem>
		<statement>
			Let <m>R</m> be a ring.
			Then <m>\ideal{\emptyset} = \set{0}</m>.
		</statement>

	</theorem>
	<proof>
		<p>	
			Observe that for all ideals <m>J</m> in <m>R</m>, <m>\emptyset\subseteq J</m>.
			In particular, one of the ideals in the right-hand side of <xref ref="eq_idealgeneratedbyset" /> is the zero ideal.
			Since the zero ideal is a subset of all ideals, the theorem follows. 
		</p>
	</proof>


    <p>
      One way to think of <m>\ideal{S}</m> is given in the following theorem.
    </p>
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given a commutative ring <m>R</m> and a subset <m>S</m> of <m>R</m>,
          <m>\ideal{S}</m> is the smallest ideal containing <m>S</m> in the sense that, if <m>J</m> is any ideal of <m>R</m> containing <m>S</m>, <m>\ideal{S}\subseteq J</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Let <m>I</m> be any ideal containing <m>S</m>.
        Thus, <m>I</m> is one of the ideals on the right-hand side of <xref ref="eq_idealgeneratedbyset" />.
        Since <m>\ideal{S}</m> is formed by the intersection of <m>I</m> with other ideals,
        <m>\ideal{S}\subseteq I</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
    	Another (often more useful) way to think about <m>\ideal{S}</m> follows.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm_idealgeneratingset">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given a commutative ring with identity <m>R</m> and a nonempty subset <m>S</m> of <m>R</m>:
          <ol>
          	<li>The set <m>I = \setof{r_1 s_1 + r_2 s_2 + \cdots + r_n s_n}{r_i\in R, \ s_j \in S,\ n\ge 1}</m> is an ideal of <m>R</m>;</li>
          	<li> <m>S\subseteq I</m>; and</li>
          	<li> <m>I = \ideal{S}</m></li>.
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
     <!-- 
 <hint>
        <p>
          Begin by showing that <m>I=\setof{r_1 s_1 + r_2 s_2 + \cdots + r_n s_n}{r_i\in R, \ s_j \in S,\ n\ge 1}</m> is an ideal containing <m>S</m>.
        </p>
      </hint>
 -->
    </theorem>
    <proof>

      <p>
        It is clear that <m>0\in I</m>,
        and that if <m>r\in R</m> and <m>x\in I</m>, <m>rx\in I</m>.
        Moreover, the sum of two <m>R</m>-linear combinations of elements of <m>S</m> is yet another <m>R</m>-linear combination of elements of <m>S</m>.
        Thus, <m>I</m> is an ideal.
        Further, if <m>s\in S</m>,
        <m>1\cdot s \in I</m>, so <m>S\subseteq I</m>.
        Therefore, <m>\ideal{S}\subseteq I</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Now assume that <m>x\in I</m>.
        Then <m>x</m> has the form <m>x = r_1 s_1 + \cdots + r_n s_n</m>.
        Each <m>s_i \in S</m>, so each
        <m>r_i s_i \in J</m> if <m>J</m> is any ideal containing <m>S</m>.
        In particular, <m>r_i s_i \in \ideal{S}</m>,
        and thus the sum <m>x = \sum r_i s_i \in \ideal{S}</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <notation>
      <p>
        If <m>R</m> is a commutative ring and
        <m>S = \set{s_1, s_2, \ldots,
        s_n}</m> is a finite subset of <m>R</m>,
        the ideal generated by <m>R</m> is often denoted by <m>\ideal{s_1 s_2, \ldots,
        s_n}</m>.
      </p>
    </notation>
    <assemblage>
    	<title>Challenge</title>
			<p>
				<statement>			
				  The ring <m>\Z[x]</m> is not a PID.
				</statement>
			</p>
    </assemblage>
    <hint>
      <p>
        Consider the ideal <m>I = \langle 2, x \rangle</m>.
      </p>
    </hint>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Suppose that <m>I = \ideal{a(x)}</m>.
        Since <m>2\in I</m>,
        <m>2 = c(x) a(x)</m> for some <m>c(x)\in \Z[x]</m>,
        so <m>\deg c(x) = \deg a(x) = 0</m>,
        and thus <m>a(x) = a\in \Z</m>.
        We also have <m>x\in I</m>, so <m>x = b(x) a</m>,
        which implies that <m>\deg b(x) = 1</m>,
        so <m>b(x) = b_1 x + b_0</m> for some <m>b_1,b_0\in \Z</m>.
        Then <m>x = (b_1 x + b_0)a</m> implies <m>b_1 a = 1</m>.
        Thus, <m>a = 1</m> or <m>a = -1</m>.
        In either case,
        <m>a</m> is a unit in <m>\Z[x]</m> so <m>1\in I</m>.
        By <xref ref="thm_idealgeneratingset">Theorem</xref>,
        there are polynomials <m>p(x),q(x)\in\Z[x]</m> such that <m>1 = 2p(x) + xq(x)</m>.
        If <m>p_0</m> is the constant term of <m>p(x)</m>,
        it follows that the constant term of <m>2p(x) + xq(x)</m> is
        <m>2p_0 = 1</m>, which is a contradiction.
      </p>
      <p>
        Thus, <m>I</m> is not principal.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="SubSec-Quotient-Rings">
    <title>Quotient Rings</title>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be a ring and <m>I</m> an ideal of <m>R</m>.
          Then elements <m>r,s\in R</m> are said to be
          <term>congruent modulo <m>I</m></term> if <m>b-a\in I</m>.
          If this is the case, we write <m>a + I = b + I</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <exploration>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given a ring <m>R</m>, ideal <m>I</m>,
          and <m>r\in R</m>, when is it the case that <m>r + I = 0 + I = I</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          When <m>r\in I</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exploration>

    <p>
      Observe that if <m>b-a \in I</m>,
      then there is some <m>x\in I</m> such that <m>b-a = x</m>,
      and so <m>b = a+x</m>.
    </p>
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be a ring and <m>I</m> an ideal of <m>R</m>.
          Then congruence modulo <m>I</m> is an equivalence relation on <m>R</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      The set of equivalence classes under this relation is denoted <m>R/I</m>.
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Since <m>0\in I</m>, <m>a-a \in I</m> for all <m>a</m>,
        so <m>a + I = a+I</m> and the relation is reflexive.
      </p>
      <p>
        Moreover, if <m>b-a \in I</m>,
        then <m>-1(b-a) = a-b \in I</m>,
        so the relation is symmetric.
      </p>
      <p>
        If <m>b-a \in I</m> and <m>c-b\in I</m>,
        then <m>(b-a) + (c-b) = c-a \in I</m>,
        so the relation is transitive.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be a ring and <m>I</m> an ideal of <m>R</m>.
          If <m>a,b,c,d\in R</m> such that
          <m>a+I = b+I</m> and <m>c+I = d+I</m>,
          then <m>(a+c) + I = (b+d) + I</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>a+I = b+I</m> and <m>c+I = d+I</m>.
        Then <m>b-a =x \in I</m> and <m>d-c = y \in I</m>.
        Adding, we have <m>(b-a) + (d-c) = (b+d) - (a+c) = x+y \in I</m>.
        Thus, <m>(b+d) + I = (a+c) + I</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be a ring and <m>I</m> an ideal of <m>R</m>.
          If <m>a,b,c,d\in R</m> such that
          <m>a+I = b+I</m> and <m>c+I = d+I</m>,
          then <m>ac + I = bd + I</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <proof>
      <p>
        As before, we observe that
        <m>b-a = x\in I</m> and <m>d-c = y\in I</m>.
        Write <m>b = x+a</m> and <m>d = c+y</m>.
        Then <m>bd = (x+a)(c+y) = xc + xy + ac + ay = ac + \underbrace{(xc+xy+ay)}_{\in I}</m>,
        so <m>bd - ac \in I</m>, and thus <m>bd + I = ac + I</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
      The previous two theorems together show that addition and multiplication on the set <m>R/I</m> is well-defined.
    </p>
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be a commutative ring with identity <m>1_R</m> and <m>I</m> an ideal of <m>R</m>.
          The set of equivalence classes modulo <m>I</m>, denoted <m>R/I</m>,
          is a commutative ring with identity <m>1_R + I</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <exploration>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R = \Z</m> and <m>I = \ideal{7}</m>.
          Find at least three distinct integers <m>x</m> such that <m>9 + I = x + I</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Such <m>x</m> include <m>-5, 2, 16</m>,
          and anything in <m>\setof{2+7m}{m\in\Z}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exploration>

    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be commutative with identity and <m>P\subsetneq R</m> a nonzero ideal.
          We say <m>P</m> is <term>prime</term>
          if whenever <m>a,b\in R</m> such that <m>ab\in P</m>,
          we have <m>a\in P</m> or <m>b\in P</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be a domain and <m>p\in R</m> be prime.
          Then <m>\ideal{p}</m> is a prime ideal.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Which of the following ideals are prime?
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\ideal{9}</m> in <m>\Z</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\ideal{11}</m> in <m>\Z</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\ideal{x^2+1}</m> in <m>\R[x]</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\ideal{x^2-1}</m> in <m>\R[x]</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\ideal{x^2-5x+6, x^4+2x^3-10x^2+5x-2}</m> in <m>\R[x]</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Not prime.
                <m>3\cdot 3= 9\in \ideal{9}</m>,
                but <m>3\notin\ideal{9}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prime.
                If <m>x\in \ideal{11}</m>, then <m>11|x</m> and 11 is prime.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prime.
                Easy explanation is that <m>R[x]/\ideal{x^2+1}</m> is isomorphic to <m>\C</m>.
                <m>\ddot\smile</m> For now, though,
                we know that <m>x^2+1</m> is irreducible,
                and <m>R[x]</m> is a PID, so irreducibles are prime.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Not prime.
                <m>x^2-1 = (x-1)(x+1)</m>,
                but <m>x\pm 1\notin \ideal{x^2-1}</m> for degree reasons.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                One may use the EA to show that <m>\gcd(x^2-5x+6,x^4+2x^3-10x^2+5x-2) = x-2</m>,
                so <m>\ideal{x^2-5x+6, x^4+2x^3-10x^2+5x-2} = \ideal{x-2}</m>.
                This is prime.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>

    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be commutative with identity and let <m>M\subsetneq R</m> be a nonzero ideal.
          We say that <m>M</m> is a <term>maximal ideal</term>
          if no proper ideal of <m>R</m> properly contains <m>M</m>.
          That is, if <m>J</m> is an ideal satisfying <m>M\subseteq J\subseteq R</m>,
          either <m>J=M</m> or <m>J=R</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      It is a fact that any ring <m>R</m> with <m>0_R\ne 1_R</m> has a maximal ideal.
      This follows from <em>Zorn's Lemma</em>;
      a rigorous exploration of Zorn's Lemma lies outside of the scope of these notes,
      but suffice it to say that Zorn's Lemma is incredibly useful in all areas of algebra for proving existence theorems.
      For example,
      a proof that every vector space has a basis relies on Zorn's Lemma.
    </p>
    <p>
      Rings with only one maximal ideal are said to be <em>local rings</em>,
      and are actively studied in modern research in commutative algebra
      (the study of commutative rings and their properties).
    </p>
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be commutative with identity and <m>I</m> an ideal of <m>R</m>.
          Then <m>I</m> is prime if and only if <m>R/I</m> is an integral domain.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Begin by assuming that <m>I</m> is prime,
        and suppose <m>(a+I)(b+I) = 0+I = I</m>.
        Then <m>ab \in I</m>, and since <m>I</m> is prime,
        either <m>a\in I</m> or <m>b\in I</m>.
        Thus either <m>a+I = 0+I</m> or <m>b+I = 0+I</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Now assume that <m>R/I</m> is a domain.
        Further, let <m>a,b\in R</m> be such that <m>(a+I)(b+I) = ab+I = 0+I</m>.
        Then <m>ab\in I</m>, and since <m>R/I</m> is a domain,
        <m>a+I = 0+I</m> or <m>b+I = 0+I</m>,
        i.e., <m>a\in I</m> or <m>b\in I</m>.
        Thus, <m>I</m> is prime.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <lemma>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be commutative with identity and <m>M</m> a maximal ideal of <m>R</m>.
          Let <m>x\in R\setminus M</m>,
          and set <m>J = \setof{xr+y}{r\in R, \ y\in M}</m>.
          Then <m>M\subsetneq J</m>,
          and thus there exist <m>r'\in R</m>,
          <m>y'\in M</m> such that <m>1 = xr'+y'</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </lemma>
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be commutative with identity and <m>I</m> an ideal of <m>R</m>.
          Then <m>I</m> is maximal if and only if <m>R/I</m> is a field.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          For the forward direction, apply the previous lemma.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </theorem>
    <proof>
      <p>
        If <m>R/I</m> is a field,
        assume <m>J</m> is an ideal of <m>R</m> that properly contains <m>I</m>.
        Let <m>x\in J\setminus I</m>;
        then <m>x+I</m> is a nonzero element of <m>R/I</m>,
        and since <m>R/I</m> is a field,
        there is some <m>y+I</m> such that <m>(xy)+I = 1+I</m>.
        Since <m>x\in J</m>, <m>xy\in J</m>.
        As <m>1+I = (x+I)(y+I) = xy+I</m>,
        we have <m>1-xy\in I\subsetneq J</m>,
        and thus <m>1 = (1-xy)+xy \in J</m>, which means <m>J = R</m>.
        Thus, <m>I</m> is maximal.
      </p>
      <p>
        Now, suppose that <m>I</m> is maximal and let <m>x\in R\setminus I</m>.
        Apply the previous lemma to obtain
        <m>1 = xr' + y'</m>, where <m>y'\in I</m>.
        Then
        <me>
          1 + I = xs+y + I = xs + I = (x+I)(y+I)
        </me>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every maximal ideal is prime.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <proof>
      <p>
        All fields are integral domains.
        Thus, if <m>I</m> is maximal,
        <m>R/I</m> is a field, thus a domain,
        and thus <m>I</m> is prime.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In a principal ideal domain, every prime ideal is maximal.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Let <m>R</m> be a PID and <m>\ideal{p}</m> a prime ideal.
        By previous work, <m>p</m> is prime.
        Suppose that <m>\ideal{p} \subseteq \ideal{m}</m>.
        Thus, <m>p\in \ideal{m}</m>, so <m>m|p</m>.
        That is, <m>p = mk</m>.
        Since <m>p</m> is prime and <m>R</m> is a domain, it is irreducible.
        Thus, either <m>m</m> or <m>k</m> is a unit.
        If <m>m</m> is a unit, then <m>\ideal{m} = R</m>.
        If <m>k</m> is a unit, then <m>m = k^{-1} p</m>,
        and thus <m>m\in \ideal{p}</m>,
        which means that <m>\ideal{m} = \ideal{p}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Thus, <m>\ideal{p}</m> is maximal.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <assemblage>
    <title>Challenge</title>
    <p>
    <statement>
      Find a commutative ring with identity, <m>R</m>, and a non-maximal prime ideal <m>P</m> of <m>R</m>.
      </statement>

    </p>
    </assemblage>

    <solution>
      <p>
        In <m>\Z[x]</m>,
        it is straightforward to see that <m>\ideal{x}</m> is prime.
        Moreover, <m>\ideal{x}\subsetneq \ideal{2,x}</m>, and thus is not maximal.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="SubSec-Homomorphisms">
    <title>Homomorphisms</title>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> and <m>S</m> be commutative rings with identity.
          A function <m>\p : R\to S</m> is a called
          <term>ring homomorphism</term>
          if it preserves addition, multiplication, and sends the identity of <m>R</m> to the identity of <m>S</m>.
          That is, for all <m>x,y\in R</m>:
          <ul>
          	<li><m>\p(x+y) = \p(x) + \p(y)</m>,</li>
          	<li><m>\p(xy) = \p(x)\p(y)</m>, and</li>
          	<li><m>\p(1_R) = 1_S</m>.</li>
          </ul>
          If <m>\p</m> is a bijection,
          we say that <m>\p</m> is an <term>isomorphism</term>
          and write <m>R\cong S</m>.
          If <m>\p : R\to R</m> is an isomorphism,
          we say <m>\p</m> is an <term>automorphism</term> of <m>R</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that the function <m>\p : Z\to \Z_{5}</m> defined by <m>\p(x) = \overline{x}</m> is a homomorphism.
          Is it an isomorphism?
          Why or why not?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Note that <m>\p(x+y) = \overline{x+y} = \overline{x} + \overline{y} = \p(x) + \p(y)</m>,
          and similarly for multiplication.
          We observe that <m>\p</m> is not an isomorphism,
          as <m>\p(2) = \p(7) = \overline{2}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>

    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be commutative with identity and <m>I</m> an ideal of <m>R</m>.
          Define <m>\p: R\to R/I</m> by <m>\p(r) = r+I</m>.
          Then <m>\p</m> is a homomorphism.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <investigation>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R = \Z_2[x]</m> and consider the map
          <m>F: R \to R</m> given by <m>F(p) = p^2</m>.
          Is <m>F</m> a homomorphism?
          An isomorphism?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </investigation>

    <exploration>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Give an example of other rings <m>R</m> and <m>S</m> and a homomorphism <m>\p : R\to S</m>.
          Show that your function is a homomorphism and determine whether or not it is an isomorphism.
          Multiple presentations
          (of different homomorphisms)
          are possible.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          One is complex conjugation, which is an isomorphism <m>\C\to\C</m>.
          Another is <m>\p : \Z_5 \to \Z_{10}</m> given by <m>\p(x) = 5x</m>
          (this isn't easy).
        </p>
