    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\p : R \to S</m> be a ring homomorphism.
          Then <m>\ker \p =\setof{r\in R}{\p(r)=0_S}</m> is the
          <term>kernel</term> of <m>\p</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be commutative with identity and <m>r\in R</m>.
          The <em><m>r</m>-evaluation map</em> <m>\p_r : R[x] \to R</m> defined by <m>\p_r(p(x)) = p(r)</m> is a homomorphism.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          This follows from the way sums and products of polynomials are evaluated.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </theorem>
    <exploration>
    	<statement>
	    	<p>What is <m>\ker \p_r</m>?</p>
	    </statement>
		<solution>
			By definition, <m>\ker \p_r</m> is the set of all
          <m>p(x)\in R[x]</m> such that <m>p(r) =0</m>, that is,
          the set of all polynomials which have <m>r</m> as a zero.
        </solution>
    </exploration>

